I recommend taking the subway, Red Line than Gold Line to avoid traffic and parking issues. Really fun for family and gives people a taste of LA's thriving urban scene.

bought a bunch of shirt for giveaway when I return home to my hometown in the Philippines. Prices are really cheap but the quality of the items I bought are really good. The prints are rubberized and made with good design.

This place is always so fun because you can get many things for a very cheap price. The baby turtles are very cute. There are a lot of souvenirs to buy and cheap clothing. There is a juice shop in the very back that sells fresh iced juices, like strawberry.
Best place to find and buy gold, diamonds, and jewelry.
Go there to do my hair.
It's a cool place to buy cheap stuff and some not so cheap....

Incredible experience and I plan to visit again. Their history exhibit about California, WWII, and Hawaii was emotional and movie. The current Japanese toy collection currently through July 2019 was really fun and interactive and better than I expected. Third Thursday of every month is free. Every Thursday after 5pm (extended hours on Thursdays till 8pm) is FREE! I highly recommend visiting there. It's also right across the street from the Gold Line's Little Tokyo station.

Highly recommend visiting the Japanese American National Museum when you are in LA. The museum does a great job of telling the story of Japanese Americans in the United States. The main exhibit covers the history of Japanese immigrants and Japanese Americans with great overviews, pictures, artifacts, primary quotes and curated perspective. The museum staff is also wonderful. We especially enjoyed Marvin Inouye and his story telling.

A good museum with lots of details on the lives of pre-WW2 Japanese immigrants to the US. The experience of leaving one's home country and everything that was familiar, to seek a better life in the US, and then to be treated like the enemy and have everything taken away, is one of unimaginable anguish and frustration, and one which this museum has elegantly chronicled. I left saddened by this story, but also inspired by the sheer resilience of this community which has contributed so much to California's rich cultural tapestry.

A nice and educational museum that shows the history and heritage of Japanese Americans throughout history. The only downside is that I wish they had more space for other exhibits but then again, the exhibits wouldn't have the opportunity to be as educational and detailed if that were the case.
The museum showed many different perspectives on the japanese community. I would definitely recommend going there. It is a trip worth taking.

I've been here before years ago but decided to enjoy more of the farmer's market side than the actual shopping area side. This time, we got to peruse a bit more and while it's packed, the parking garage is pretty big and can fit a lot of cars.  This place has upgraded a lot through the years and it made us feel like we were at Disneyland. It was a nice mix of shopping, dining and family experience.

Holy moly, what a gorgeous mall! The space is landscaped very well and the mall itself is easy to navigate. I love the atmosphere of this mall and how accessible it is to locals and tourists. The overall style and character of the mall is top-notch. I was visiting from out of town and stopped by three times because I was so taken by it. Such a lovely spot!

Fun place with lots of options to eat, shop, and hang out. Highly recommend the sushi place on the 3rd floor if you have some money to drop. The catch is that you have to spend 25 dollars or more at most places to get a validation. Though eating out usually covers this. Only complaint is that the parking is a little tight can can be difficult to manuver.

This mall is becoming a DUMP! Routinely escalators do not work. Security allows dogs (non ADA dogs) into the mall. Homeless sleeping in the massage chairs. Today two down escalators were not working as well as the elevator. Security had no clue.  Never see them walking around. Absolutely useless. Management needs to clean house.

It's an amazing place full of wonderful shops! There are so many food places to eat from that are very good. There are also some really good dessert places to visit too. You can find a lot little shops that sell a variety of items from anime/manga, traditional Japanese clothing/objects, and others. I really recommend coming here!

This cool hidden house was a nice escape from the busy street. On a day less crowded you feel like you're in country side and almost forget you're in LA.
I thought these translations were interesting inside the house. From Spanish to English they are quite different. I was humored by it.
Great food and great service. We had to wait a bit because weekends are first come first served basis. But once we got a table, worth the wait.

The Avila Adobe is the oldest homestead in all of Los Angeles. I visited the adobe on an overcast and drizzly January afternoon. It seemed as if my brother and I were the only people there. The docent was beyond friendly, and full of interesting facts, both adobe-related, and not. After a half-hour conversation, we had the adobe pretty much to ourselves and we took our time wandering about. The space houses some beautiful relics. On a cold and damp day with little human distraction, there's more than a whiff of the eldritch to the place.
Free museum with lots of history. Very cool stop. Great location on Olvera Street.
Very nice place, I love how you can see and feel the way these people lived back then. I recommend everyone to visit this place Los Angeles.

The Chinese American Museum is an amazing place to know about American-Chinese history and culture. The exhibitions there are limited, but the museum is free and it's definitely a good, educational experience. The parking though, it's a but limited and you have to pay for it.
Wonderful museum with create small exhibits that are free to the public. Also in an historic part of the city and in a building that is the oldest hotel in Los Angeles

We walked in here because we were hot and it was the only place that had AC. So glad we did, we ended up staying and visiting the entire museum. Definitely came out with more info than I had before going in.
Great historical account of the founding families of old to New Chinatown. Small but powerful.
Great history about LAs early  Chinese founders & contributors.  Worth the time
Very important place the group are changing information continuesly

This museum/gallery is always great. With rotating exhibits that are both sociopolitical and artistic, the Museum of Social Justice is always worth a visit when you're in the area. Our students at Angeles Workshop School, being very engaged in revolutionary politics, love the topics and themes explored by the activist artists shown here.
Very educational

The Admission: FREE. One of the historic sites on Olvera Street. 

The Museum: Very Very Very small museum. Took about less than 5 minutes to see all the display. 

If you are shopping or dining on Olvera Street, pop in and check it out. FREE admission and won't take too much of your time.
Aku tidak pernah kesini,tanpa kesana aku tahu tempat ini sangat bagus

Do not miss the Museum of Contemporary Art in Bangkok! Not only is it a wonderful museum it is also a stunning piece of modern architecture. You'll need all day and then some more, a dream for any art buff there's five floors of spectacular exhibits. On the ground floor there's a restaurant, garden and an interactive experience. Take the family.  I loved it and next time I'm in Bangkok I'll be heading back for another look.👍🌟🌟🌟🌟🌟

The Museum of Contemporary Art is from 2012. It is a private museum housed in a large building. 

There is no double pricing. Same price for a Thai and a foreigner. If you  are more than 60, you can enter for free. Not only Thais, but also foreigners. The price for a regular ticket is TB 250.

Obviously, most of the items on display in this museum are from Thailand, but on the fifth floor there is an interesting collection of foreign items.

Next to all items on display is a label with information in Thai and in English. 

You are allowed to use a camera inside the museum, but you cannot use a flash. There is one exception: you are not allowed to take pictures inside the special Robert Green collection on the fifth floor.

There is a coffee shop on the ground floor. There is a car park in the basement. 

The staff are friendly and helpful.

If you are interested in contemporary art, this place is definitely worth a visit.

Oh....
This is an ....hard to say.
They declare that this is a contemporary museum but this museum does not explore the comprehensive contemporary art all over the world because it’s simply this is a private museum owned by one business man.the collection is rely on his taste.of course this museum is playing a key role for collecting national artists of Thailand but mainly the collection is reflected on his preference.
I really love this spot because I can enjoy the most sophisticated art works in Bangkok.
I’ll come back here again.

Great museum. 
Beautiful building. Lots of great surrealism and some traditional Thai art. 
Definitely worth going although it's hard to get to, since the nearby train is not operational yet. Try to make sure your cab driver knows the place. Took us some time to get there but was worth it 👍👍

Surprisingly beautiful (and modern) structure that houses mostly modern and some traditional art. Peacefully quiet—not many locals seem aware it exists. The art is fascinating—a modern reinterpreting traditional Thai aesthetic forms. Lovely reprieve from the hot chaos of the city.

This museum is great. I visited a Saturday and the entrance was free. I enjoyed a free tour on one of the exhibitions that was conducted by an art professor for free. 
It's  a minimalistic but warm museum. It's the most relaxed museum I have visited.  I felt at home... The employees are very nice and welcoming.

Great artistic exhibits hosted in the center of Little Tokyo. I spontaneously stumbled upon an exhibit hosted here after lunch in Little Tokyo. The staff told me that the tickets were free for the day. We were very lucky to see the beautiful creations of art inside. The building exterior also offers a great backdrop for creative photo shoots.

Paid $8 admission with a Student ID. On a rainy Wednesday afternoon the museum was very quiet and peaceful with few visitors. Two artists were featured in the exhibits I saw. This I appreciated, as it gives one a fuller picture of the artist's style, interests, and thoughts. Also, for those who use public transportation, it's easily accessible via the metro gold line.

The art is really cool and I'm glad I went, but for a building that size, the amount of art felt little. They could have definitely used the space better to add more. I finished the entire wall around and observed every image in about 20 minutes.. and yes I take the time to observe images. I dont just scroll through like an Instagram post.

Great exhibition space in Little Tokyo.  The galleries are larger in scale than the downtown location of MOCA, allowing for more diversity in the exhibitions.  No permanent collection at the Geffen, so check the website to see what's on view.  Exhibitions vary in quality and scope.  Note that a ticket bought at the Geffen will also get you into the downtown branch the same day, and vice versa.

This year the show had some impressive work but not as outstanding in the years before. But of course the art world fluctuates They'll n quality constantly so no one is to blame. They do need to place some more convenient places to eat (and affordable) and place clear signs letting you know where the restrooms are. One shouldn't have to wander around looking for food and the facilities.

Great choice for a date night or anyone looking to explore DTLA. Make sure to plan out your journey and or have a map handy as it can be difficult to wander through the streets without it. I highly recommend checking out the art for sale on the street as well as the food trucks / stands. Great experience for someone visiting the city and locals alike.
Pleasure walking tents rows as friendly Services or owners are skilled crafts. Jewelries,  items. Good  fresh vegetables,  fresh fruits,  veggies. 👍🌿🌷🍜🎶

Art Walk DTLA is always a great cultural and social event that happens monthly in Downtown Los Angeles. Vendors and art collectives come together along with throngs of gatherers for the viewing and purchase of latest-day art renderings and originals from local artists.

Awesome! The only critique is that you have to pay to get into the food truck area... why? Your paying for food? Parking is impossible. Just take metro! The crafts are awesome. I always end up leaving with something... hand made soap, interesting magnets, sunglasses a hat. Great place to meet with friends and enjoy the night walking around and seeing different studios.

I always have the best time at the Grammy Museum downtown. It’s one that I frequent often, because of the many events and exhibits that are circulated. One of the best exhibits they’ve had was the Whitney Houston exhibit which featured many of her artifacts and costumes from throughout the 80s, 90s, and 00s. They currently are spotlighting Dolly Parton and her many costumes over the years. I also enjoy the frequent events that take place here. The Grammy Museum opens its doors to artists for small concerts, like the recent Thelma Houston experience. There are also film screenings and discussions with industry executives. I highly suggest grabbing tickets to an exhibit which interests you. It is a great place to start building your music knowledge, but more than that, it’s an opportunity to celebrate some of the best the music world has offered us. Five stars!

Not bad. Would love a guided experience; not sure if that's available. $15 admission is a little high for the size compared to most other LA area museums, but it's def an affordable fee. Could have watched the Grammy show performances for hours.

A nice museum to check out, especially for music lovers or an activity to do on a rainy day. A lot of the exhibits are interactive and the museum itself has collected a great amount of historical artifacts regarding all genres of music. The pricing itself is decent, they do offer a variety of discounts. However, this museum is probably best suited for those who are using travel card packages such as Go Los Angeles! where admission to this museum is already included.

The Grammy Museum L.A. LIVE has some cool popular music relics and studio music experiences for visitors. It’s like the Grammy Museum in Nashville but a tad smaller. Level 2 was closed so only got to see two floors of memorabilia. Would’ve liked to purchased a basic Grammy Awards Museum men’s shirt but all that was left was XXL shirts:(

It's a great and fun museum to visit (especially for music lovers) and to learn about history of music and the Grammys. Many interactive exhibitions and historical artifacts from some of the greatest and most recognized artists of all genres. From time to time they change some of the exhibitions. Pricing is OK, and they have a variety of discounts. It is near Staples Center and Microsoft Theater, the area has nice restaurants and places to visit.

The cathedral is magnificent and underneath is just as wonderful. Marble crypts, stained glass arts, and chapels. All these is worth a visit.

Attending a mass is an added benefit. A good way to see Catholic traditions and feel the welcome of a community. On Sundays, there are only two morning English masses and a Spanish noon mass. If you're an early riser, stop for a mass after touring the facility.
This one of the Cathedral you should come and visit. It’s amazing. The structure is modern and glorious!! The garden, the shop is also good to buy souvenirs. Great to take a time to pray.

A beautiful & respectful piece of public archetecture for the Los Angeles community.  I wasn't there for a service, but just wanted to see some of the components of this religious heritage art work piece that has been built for tge people of our community.
I will enjoy returning again to better experience some of what I missed on this, my first-ever visit.

It's beautiful, spiritual and a peaceful exisistamce in getting away from the hustle and bustle of the day. The gardens offer aelcome quaint place for reflection. An absolute must for anyone regardless of Faith. All is welcome to come over anytime.
Striking modern architecture with a welcoming spirit. The grounds manage to distance the rest of LA, and each step feel profound.

I was really happy to visit this iconic building, and admission was free. The staff were very friendly!
The place to take beautiful photos, at the top of the building the 360-degree city view is spectacular.
Don't miss it out if you visit LA. Unforgettable experience.
Amazing building to visit. You can really feel the history of the city and the views are just beautiful and the best part is that it is for free.
Great historic building to see the los angeles skyline for free!

Must visit place in LA.
Free entry. 
Can visit top floor to get birds eye view of the city. 
Lots to photograph. 
Learn about LA and the building.

City Hall got fantastic views of Los Angles city from the top floor.Its a must in Los Angles site seeing.On the entrance you have to fill a small form and security will body check and then you can take a lift to upstairs.A nice and clean toilet is also free to use.City hall is very beautiful from inside.Many different gates but entry is only from one gate so make sure you are going towards right gate. 
#cityhallla
Este es un outlet donde se pueden encontrar negocios de.ropa y demás cosas. Buenos.precios.
Hhh

Service once we got inside was very very good. We ordered the Mexican Prawns, the Cesear combination and the crab cakes and shared it all. Everything was delicious and we were all stuffed upon leaving. Can't wait to go back. Next time will definitely get oysters too.

Love this place! everything is always fresh!!! I never get the fried items, which is weird for me... because the Charbroiled items are so good!!!   I love the giant Prawns and Scallops... crab cakes, Sea Bass...and there sauces!!!! all of them soooooo good! You will not be disappointed.  Fast Service... outside eating only FYI.

My first time visiting Ocean Seafood Restaurant. In our asian culture we love Sunday brunch. Dim Sum is a must and this place had some pretty decent items. 

We went at one of the most busiest times, so we had to wait a solid 40 minutes for a table. Highly recommend arriving early. 

One of the most fun part of Dim Sum is the ladies with carts of steamed foods. They didn’t circulate a wide range of items. Upon my realization, I could have just ordered items with the server. Takes away from the fun, but this can also alleviate the wait times most customers feel waiting for a table. 

Otherwise nice place to visit when you are visiting California.

Very nice restaurant. The entrance staircase is beautiful, mirrors and fountains. Food tastes amazing. The food is already cooked and the waiters walk around with carts with the food. You can see what you want and pick it. Very good prices.

We stopped by this lovely restaurant and sat at the bar yesterday. The staff was very nice and the chef was very patient with a couple seeking recommendations on what dish to order. He was very attentive to the customers sitting close by. Their service was great and the food was delicious. I would definitely stop by again on my next visit to Los Angeles.

It's a really small place but the mochi here is excellent! The place does seem a bit old but it's not bad. The prices are also really great! It's quite cheap. The staff is friendly. I recommend coming here!

The selection they had when I went were a bit bizarre or odd for my tastes, and I tried the Mint Chip and it wasn't what I am accustomed to, so I opted for the Vanilla flavor, which was good... but generally I never order Vanilla at an Ice Cream parlor because it's so basic, plain and uninspired. The service here was nice and friendly, as they let you sample flavors too.

Came here on a late night visit. Not your typical ice cream parlor. Had three different sorbet flavors.  Blackberry, Earl grey, and Guava. Pretty tasty but nothing special. It's one of those places I will try again after a year has gone by.

Great place to stop in for some after dinner sweets!!!

Super delicious mochi's that come in various flavours such as green tea, plum wine, and black sesame, highly recommend the black sesame flavour. 

Restaurant is a bit aged but still really clean. Service is good but could be friendlier. 5 stars is for food only.

I don’t know if it’s me or the Matcha ice cream is really taste wired. It supposed be a bit bitter and herbal but I tasted it soured somehow. However the green tea mochi was still good so I leave it 3 starts.

This place has amazing food and ambiance! Don't miss out on eating here if you're a Dodgers fan! They specialize in roast beef dips which are all amazing. Their potato salad is wonderful and all of the cashier's are super nice. I love seeing them all dressed up in their Dodger gear on game days!! There is also a lot of old baseball memorabilia, mostly specific to Dodger stadium, making the shop sort of a mini-museum.

This is the best spot to come for an authentic classic french dipped sandwich experience! I ordered the beef french 'double' dip with blue cheese. All the sides are delicious and the deserts are great too. Parking is easy in the lot across the street but be careful during rush hour. You will not be disappointed if you choose to eat here but don't be expecting a fancy sit down restaurant, more like a delicious weekend lunch spot after a sporting event. Enjoy!

A Los Angeles classic. I've been going my whole life, and it never disappoints. All of the food I've had there is good. I tried the pastrami sandwich for the first time on my last visit and it was stellar. I recommend ordering a "Beef Double Dip" if you can't decide. Add some cheese and apply their in-house mustard yourself for a unique taste. The lines look long but they move pretty quick. It's a neat place were all walks of life come together.

The original and the best. The lamb and beef dip were incredible. Meat was tender and juicy and packed with flavour. This would be a favourite spot of mine if I were a local. If you passing through. Stop for lunch or dinner. You won't be disappointed!

Phillipe's is just so good, and so very traditional. They have the “French Dipped Sandwich” that is the specialty of the house and can have it with either roast beef, roast pork, leg of lamb, turkey, pastrami or ham served on a fresh baked French roll which has been dipped in the gravy of the roasts. Swiss, American, Cheddar, Monterey Jack or Blue cheese can be added and you can get it not dipped, does once, or twice! I recommend twice, it is just so good. I also suggest getting their mustard there which has a kick to it with Horseradish in it! Definitely recommended.

The atmosphere and music is great! I was immediately greeted by the owner and given a comfortable seat. The staff is polite and professional. I even got the opportunity to chat with one of the cooks. My food arrived quickly and it was delicious! My husband and I each ordered the 3 meat platters and we could not finish them! The beef ribs and brisket are tops! Then I ordered the peach cobbler..... OMG!!!! IT WAS ABSOLUTELY BEAUTIFUL AND DELICIOUS!!! It was well worth my decision to stop eating to save room for it. I have never had a peach cobbler that wasn't home made that I loved as much as this peach cobbler!!!!!!!!!! I WILL DEFINITELY be coming back to Spring Street Smokehouse and I advise you stop in too!! 😋

Don't good BBQ in Chinatown? You bet. They have a good tap selection of beers also, but it was lunchtime so I didn't have any. 

My sides weren't dirt friendly, but we're tasty. I had the mac&cheese and chili. My entree was e brisket! 

I do wish that the spicy BBQ and the chili were spicier.

It was a good sign when I saw firemen wasting there. "Go where the firemen eat, is a great guideline.

Words cannot fully describe how delicious the food is here. I checked in here and got a free chocolate chip cookie and it was SO good. The barbecue sauce that they put on their food is one of the best that I've ever had. The workers were very helpful since it was our first time there. Will be recommending family and friends.

Belated birthday dinner! I loved my beef ribs, husband loved the special: stuffed, smoked chicken thigh wrapped in bacon. Side dishes ample, dessert (warm bread pudding) amazing. Great beer list, knowledgeable staff. A favorite!

I'm a southern boy and have lived in South Carolina, North Carolina, and Texas. I've tried some of the best BBQ restaurants in America. I have worked for some amazing BBQ restaurants in the south and now I make my own. But gotta say, the pulled pork sandwich I had here was one of the best I've had since I can remember. The meat was flavored full of delicious hickory smoke and you could see the smoke rings in the pork. Low and slow. I was told these guys have a smoker that's over 15 years old. That alone makes them light years better than the competition. It's a huge advantage and personally I see no need to eat  BBQ anywhere else in LA. Of course the atmosphere of bbq restaurants in California is quite different from the whole mom and pop country store style joints I'm used to back home, but as far as flavor is concerned this place was incredible. Top notch. 🙏💯🔥

If you are selective and read the reviews,  chances are you will pick wisely.  I had the cream of potato soup, brussels sprouts and the sauteed  sole. All were very good.   The beer selection was a disappointment . Ambience was pleasant and service good.  I tried to beat hotel prices but did not succeed. With tip, everything cost about $75.
My preferred place for quality American food. Great hospitality. Next time I'll be back with my friends. Prices were appropriate. Food is similar to a place in San Francisco I liked.
My preferred spot for quality American food. Food was super flavorful. This place has a cool design. Reminds me of a restaurant in Philadelphia that I enjoyed.

This place is nestled in the heart of DTLA and I appreciate the history that this old firehouse once was.  The bar is small, but the bartenders are attentive.  Didn't have dinner, but will try next time.

Found this place by chance as looking for somewhere to eat near where we was staying. So a lovely atmosphere inside and so chilled. Loved our booth with the light and could feel the history there. 

Our server Chad was lovely and so helpful. 

I had the meatloaf and the hubs had truffle fried chicken. Both amazing and one of the best dinners we've eaten on our Honeymoon so far (2 weeks in). 

We had to have one of the desserts, hard choice but went for the Lemon Meringue and it was so delicious, couldn't fault it. 

Drinks were lovely also. 

Overall we had a fantastic time here and the costs were reasonable (after Vegas and San Francisco and our home town London). 

Thanks
I had a very good cappuccino bagel with cream cheese and lox.  Very attentive staff.  Superb place to get breakfast or lunch.

We had dinner,  then came back for dessert,  then the next morning for breakfast.  The food was all delicious... and the service was fantastic.  The vegetarian options were yummy and my wife enjoyed her carnivorous meals!

I totally enjoyed this place, the food is incredible, and also the shower rooms were not bad for public. It was a little chilly inside, so that was not totally cool. The service is good. I will most definitely consider returning once again if I ever land the possibility. Me as well as my pal got the salad as well as we were not dissatisfied. My one idea is to maintain the chilly outside. Thanks!

Food was very good & reasonable for LA. Their specialty cocktails are very good as is their wine list. It is a vibrant cafe with eclectic patrons. Lots of energy in this smaller restaurant. Not too much on the romantic side...that's what room service at the Ace Hotel is for! I would highly recommend Best Girl for an energetic evening or before dining  if attending the Ace Theater.♡
Everything was fine, the cocktails (3-6pm happy hours), oysters, food, service. Love the place, atmosphere and rooftop bar. Would love to stay at the hotel for the complete experience

Great, small restaurant. I’ve been coming here for years, consistently good food, drinks, and service. The mixed plate appetizers, chicken pot pie, and white sangria are my favorites. Highly recommend.

This is love from the first sight. 
Everything made here with love and meticulous attention to details. Your soul and body will be the happiest after the visit.

I've been a regular here since I started working in downtown. I don't know how authentic the dishes are but it doesn't matter becuase they are so delicious!! Whenever I have friends visit LA this place is the first meal I always treat them with and people love it too! Their seafood dishes are so exceptional and everyone works here are super nice too.
brazilian food and service here is very good. it's so delicious. i've had nothing but pleasant experiences here and plan to keep coming back.
Super friendly staff, awesome food with good vegetarian options. The potato balls are amazing

Had an awesome breakfast here one quiet Saturday morning.  Waitress was so awesomely friendly and funny.  On her suggestion I got the corned beef hash and eggs with potatoes and toast.  So glad I asked - the corned beef hash was awesome.  I was a little surprised I got the potatoes about a minute after the eggs and toast came out but I'm not complaining.

Would definitely go back again and recommend to anyone looking for a great diner downtown.

A classic that exudes old downtown LA. Great pastrami sandwiches, great deli meats all around. Lunch specials are always a steal and come out real quick. That being said, this really is a working mans lunch spot. You can expect to be get in and out in under 30 minutes and be completely full. The clincher? The best patty melt in the city.

My wife and I were visiting from Chicago. The service was spectacular. Our waitress knew all the regular customers names, and was beyond helpful and polite. The food was exactly what I would expect from a good deli. A very pleasant experience!

I go here when I'm hungry for a classic pancake/french toast breakfast for under $10. This downtown location offers many hearty breakfast options including steak and eggs and omelets. Because there are so many restaurants in the area, this place is never crowded and it's usually a good breakfast pick up before work.

This is a classic Jewish deli.  It looks like a deli, smells like a deli, feels like a deli, and yes, tastes like a deli.  

There were three of us, and despite its unnecessarily large menu (as most delis have) we all ordered the Pastrami Reuben.  It didn't come with thousand island, but we soon corrected that and we were off to the races.  

Everything was greasy, meaty and really filled you up .  The fries were ok, a bit limp for my taste, and the fruit bowl was also exactly what you'd expect.   No surprises and no let-downs.

The service was very friendly!

My partner and I went to this restaurant for our anniversary. Everyone was very welcoming and made us feel special. The food was like home made French food. 
The crab salad was amazing! However, everything we ordered was delicious. 
We are definitely coming back.

Nice site for quality French food. i give this place two thumbs up. really nothing but great experiences here, so i will be back. this place has a nice design. makes me feel like i in nashville again.

A lovely spot for a date night, I've come here for a cozy dinner with my husband a few times. I planned a holiday luncheon for my team at work this past December and the venue handled it beautifully! We had privacy, they let us take our time and didn't rush us, we got to play a game while eating dessert, and the bill was not bad at the end of the day! I will definitely be looking to host more events here.
Food is good. Service is great. I just don't understand why this restaurant has a French name when there are practically no French dish on the menu. It has plenty of pasta dishes though.
french food, super delicious. Everyone at our table was quite pleased. Service treated us so kindly. The place has a nice atmosphere.

Tried out Nick & Stef's based on a recommendation yesterday & it was good. Service was great. Food was in my opinion a bit over priced, but was good none the less. Ordered my steak medium & received it medium well. My daughter ordered medium rare & got medium. But regardless, the food was good. Drinks were mixed well. Note to truck & full size SUV owners & tall folks in general... The parking structure is on the first floor in the same complex/building as the restaurant but only has a 6 ft 6 inch clearance. Super LOW.

Extremely good steak, and sides are good too. But there were some things that weren't perfect. One of us got his steak a little bit overcooked, not Medium on all sides as he wanted. Also they bought him broussels sprouts instead of Fries, but they gave him his right side dish very fast. One spoon wasn't completely clean. But that are all, that was not good the Rest was perfect. The waitress was very very kind and friendly. The Service was overall just super good. But because of this little issues it is not 5 stars in my opinion, still absolutely worth a try.

Service was fantastic. Cocktails were mixed nicely. Setting is comfortable and contemporary. Steak was great. Dine LA menu had everything you would have otherwise ordered off of the regular menu. Will be coming back next time I am in need of a nicely cooked slab of premium meat.

I ordered the New York steak! While it's better than other steakhouses like Outback, I'm disappointed to say that this steak doesn't beat Uncle John's or how my mom would always cook it. Maybe because my cut of steak was below average or I have different taste buds. However, the steak was juicy and pretty tender. Would I go back the next time I visit LA? Probably, except getting a ribeye this time because that's how I usually eat my steaks from my mom.

Great service, great food, assuming you enjoy a good steak. Nice and quiet. Gives a bit of a retro vibe. As of 01-20-2019 watch out for construction in the area. Worth the trip to downtown Los Angeles.

Had a nice meal of wings with my 11yo daughter on a late Saturday afternoon. The staff was friendly and welcoming, the food was very good, and the ambience was nice. Wings were great !!! We will definitely returm.
The Best Wings I ever had! The smoke adds another layer of flavor. Karaoke night was a lot of fun!
Wonderful exhibit. Completely free.You will find it in the courtyard of these huge glass and steel buildings so don't let that confuse you!

This is a great small space that shows different forms of art. The parking is good there is a large parking structure below the venue. The parking is validated at the venue. The space is small but they use the area they have well and even have a small gift shop tailored to the current works on display. The staff was helpful and friendly.

I’ve been to the Annenberg space for photography at least 20 times over the last five years. This is a premier place for photographs and for learning about whatever the subject matter is at the time of the exhibit. It’s free for the lectures and to go into the museum so that’s a nice thing$ At the present time does an exhibit about animals, see live and conservation. It’s definitely worth checking this place out but definitely call before you come down here as sometimes they may be closed between exhibits. The parking is at a major discount when you come here but make sure you bring your ticket up to the counter to be validated.

Kinda small space with poor street access set amid shiny, towering edifices to Hollywood's extremely wealthy. DO NOT FORGET TO HAVE PARKING VALIDATED because it's $4.50 per 12 minutes otherwise in the neighboring building. 
All that said, we saw a beautiful exhibit of Joel Sartore's Photo Ark project - a little ironic in light of the surrounding excess.

The ASP is a very small museum but with phenomenal exhibits. The museum is located at Century City neighborhood by 2000 Ave of the Stars bldg. Admission is always free. Public parking is available around the area. We went to see the Ark exhibit. It was truly amazing and quite an experience seeing those endangered animal species photographed. Staff are helpful and professional. Overall, I highly recommend this museum.

Free admission to enjoy priceless pieces of are is what Hammer offers. 

Modern to the classics are covered. Small groups of collections are scattered across two primary floors of displays. Rembrandt to Marvel are all here for you to enjoy. 

The classics is a small area while most of the collections are modern. Two hours is plenty of time to see it all. Including the newest piece from UCLA visuals. 

We will go back again soon. Bring the family and there is a new nice restaurant on the patio floor. Make it a date.

The hammer is a world class modern art museum located in the heart of Westwood. It has excellent exhibitions and architecture, and would arguably be worth a visit even if the art was less notable. The fact that it's free for students doesn't hurt either.
There are a lot of things to see and do in this museum. The place is a perfect place for bonding with your kids. It is also educational, too. I definitely recommend this place.

The museum's permanent collection is small but breathtaking, Van Gogh, Degas, Sargent, Daumier and many more...stunning. The contemporary collection is provoking too. We stopped at the new restaurant , looked at the menu but was more than we wanted to spend at a museum. Plenty of lower price options in the neighborhood. Great bookstore/ gift shop interesting selection. Over all a great place,free admission,$7 parking but they really need a simple kiosk selling coffee and cookies.
I don't know much about art, but I still think it is worth visiting.The atmosphere inside is nice. And the admission is free. You should definitely try the 677 dollar chair.

Skirball center has free parking for visitors. They are located near the Getty museum(6min) and it has little garden. From the parking lot, you can walk through little garden and enjoy the beautiful plants. As you approach to the Main gate, you will find  building with glass doors. When I went in, front desk person directed us to ticket place. We arrived early so we went inside the store and looked at many beautiful things they sell. One of the item was art work done about Proverb 31 and was decorated with various colored glass(It cost several hundreds of dollars). Throughout the center, there were many people helping us to be directed to Noah's Ark place. One lady gave very fun story telling for kids. Noah's ark was brilliantly made from all the recycled things. I was so surprised how they made the place look so artistically. Kids enjoyed so much! They ended up spending full 90 minute which is given time from when you were admitted. They even have historical artifacts displayed. I loved time here. I would Highly recommend this place. If you can't reserve online tickets due to sold out, you can still visit there and buy the ticket onsite.

Went for the Ruth Bader Ginsburg exhibit, which was super well done. We also enjoyed exploring some of the Jewish museum. Everything was very well done and engaging. It costs $12 per person to get in, you can park for free across the street, and they even had umbrellas for the walk to and from the car since it was raining!

This place is Rich in Jewish history and whether you are Jewish or not it is an awesome place to explore and learn. They also have this huge Noah's Arc replica for the kids to play in that is fantastic. The kids love it and I wish my bedroom looked like it as a kid. Thursdays a free and we did not have to pay to park.

Had a nice afternoon at Skirball. Wasn't sure what to expect coming here but left very impressed with the overall mission of the museum/organization. Big plus if you have kids...their Noah's Ark exhibit will be sure to please the little ones.

Beautiful venue! Excellent choice of venue for the Extra Ancestral show, which was incredible! Big props to Beto for curating such important artistic work. The vibe was so positive, everyone was into it!

Excellent museum. Their dinosaur exhibit is really extensive and diverse. If you like birds, they have a really retro, old school exhibit, filled with hundreds of taxidermic birds. Make sure to go to the bottom floor for the "kids" section. It was really cool and had live animals and insects to check out. CA teachers get in free with a pay stub or staff ID.
It's a small and very well curated museum in the center of UCLA, with better exhibitions than suggested by its unassuming looks.

Tucked away in the midst of UCLA campus, it's a little gem in Los Angeles. Admission is free and opens at noon.  Informative docents and guides are readily available and the walk-through is very pleasant.  Paid parking can be a tough challenge but it's not too far from the museum. Plan ahead and enjoy!

Seeing "The Art of African Blacksmiths" exhibit was an awakening for me.  It seems they've been forging steel for longer than the rest of the planet by hand.

The designs and attention to detail is striking.  Tools, weapons, chastity devices, neck and waist adornments, headgear - it's quite humbling.

Everything is beautifully displayed and there are videos showing the Blacksmiths meticulously crafting some of what's on display.  Educational for all ages.

An absolute pleasure for a short visit.  Free (except for parking), well maintained and nice family friendly museum. Insider tip: We go on sundays when they usually have arts and crafts for younger kids.

This place is beautiful beyond what words can describe. The atmosphere here is incredible. It is very alive and fresh. I love that it is close to my favorite places. I want to come here every day!! Just make sure to bring the right tennis shoes. 100% recommend!

Strolled through this remarkable garden at the start of a hike to explore the UCLA campus.  It was great 50 years ago. It has only gotten better since.  Visit many different vegetation types in one place.

The main beauty of this garden is its trees, so don't expect to be blown away by colorful flowers every where. However, the garden has lots of trees from around the world and we enjoyed our visit. This garden is free and I recommend that.
Beautiful garden. Very peaceful. Whether you want to see nature, eat your lunch or just relax, you can come here.
Great and relaxing garden to keep the stress away from students. Great walk for guests to enjoy the beautiful plants that grow in California climates. Just take a walk and leave the sadness behind.

This is an oasis of great food and Japanese groceries. The only complaint I have is the lack of seating. If you want to grab a quick lunch, look somewhere else, but if you want great food at a good price and are willing to wait for a table. This place is great. Plus the little boutiques and the grocery store is amazing.

Awesome place. Great food court, authentic Asian foods. A must for those shopping for Japanese goods, and food items. They have everything you need to make some awesome Japanese food for a get together at home. Or just pick up some prepared sushi platters. Its Japan in chicago!

Mitsuwa is a great place. They have a lot of specialty items you can't get elsewhere (obviously) and their food court is awesome. I love to go here for lunch and grab a few grocery items that I can't buy other places. And the bakery is wonderful!

THIS PLACE IS SWEET. Japanese bookstore. Asian bakery. Amazing food court. Grocery store has amazing variety of Asian goods. My only recommendation for the food court is GO THERE EARLY, not on the weekends. (Crazy busy.)

Great Japanese market with a wonderful food court.

I always enjoy coming here and love eating lunch here.  It is always very crowded and finding a table is hard. I wish they could find a way to add more tables.  I still come :)
The store is very clean and everyone working here is so nice and helpful.

burgers and the setting here is better than most. Service is always awesome even when they have a full house. The service here is attentive. The bill was average for the menu. This place has positive reviews for a reason.

One of the only stands that serve Vienna Beef hot dogs (the best!), and Marty's does everything right- grilled to order, fresh produce and buns, excellent chili, great customer service, and a really pretty location with a very cool vibe. I only wish they were open at night!  Been loving Marty's for over 30 years!!!

Marty's is amazing. Simple and delicious. I had a combo, hot dog on a burger, with cheese and chili and it was one of the best things I've eaten in California. When I come back to LA I will hit this place every time.

Been wanting to try this place for awhile - HOWEVER, not only are they slow (3rd in line for 10 mins with no chance to order in sight), but I watched the guy grab a big pile of raw meat (for steak sandwich?) & then simply wipe his hand on his apron. He immediately began touching multiple things - including bags/other items he handed to customers. That was the moment I left. Seriously guys, how about some proper food handling training?!

Ordered Marty's Hamburger Stand because I had a promotional code I needed to use, and it sounded amazing on an empty stomach. I had the beef burger with avocado, special sauce, ketchup, a fried egg, tomato, onions and sprouts. It was very delicious and just what I wanted. Everything was perfect except the fried egg was a little soggy on the outside, and the rootbeer I had ordered spilled out a bit. Other than that I would definitely order again.
Q rico👍
Awesome place
Exelente servicio

Got to restaurant around 8:30...I thought that should be ample time to still get a quality meal because they closed at 10:00. Wait service was very good but our meals arrived with only the meat hot; the rice and plantain were lukewarm and the beans a bit warmer. The flavor was mediocre, no popping flavor like I had hoped for. We ate our meal but I'd be hard pressed to go again. Late or not the food and service should be the same. I was very disappointed.

My once favorite Cuban food restaurant. Was introduced to this place when I was in college a couple of decades ago and have been coming here ever since. The food quality dipped down for a few years, as did the chicken piece sizes, but it's recovered mostly since then. 

This is straight comfort food for me. I love their signature garlic chicken and roasted pork. Their halibut is pretty good as well as long as they dinner overcook the fish. The ox tail stew isn't half bad and so rich. My favorite is their plantains. So simple yet so tasty.

Always delicious! I ordered the Famous Versailles Garlic Chicken. I can never have enough garlic and they did not disappoint. Perfectly cooked, crispy skin on the outside, and juicy flavorful meat on the inside. This will always be my go to with extra plantains please!

I love Versailles and have been going here for over 20 years. The only thing I get is the garlic chicken with extra sauce, because the sauce is so good. This is also a great place if you are gluten free since they have many options.

super delicious Cuban fare. Oxtail stew, beef tongue, cuban sandwiches and more grace this establishment. A long standing family tradition, Versailles is a cut above the rest in providing unwavering flavor that is impossible to get tired of. Their rice and beans are surpassed only by their plantains, with a delicious savory sweetness that is sure to melt the heart of any foodie. Lots of love for Versailles, and I hope it can stay open for ever.

The rolls were delicious and fairly priced. I recommend the Pink Lady roll (shrimp tempura and deep fried salmon) as well as the crispy rice and Hell's rolls. The atmosphere was welcoming and sports were on TV. Service was good and we would definitely come back again.

They have some of the most succulent and delicious yellow tail I've tasted in this city. There is rarely a wait and generally the service is great if you're good with making eye contact when you need something. All of the specialty rolls are delicious but just be careful not to over-order as they're big. Lively atmosphere and great for dates.

Very nice place on Wilshire with excellent food and fine prices. 
A very friendly atmosphere and if you sit at the bar, you can watch the chefs prepare your food.
Very good!
Absolutely love this place. Food is fresh and tasty. Service is excellent.
Great place! Always fresh and yummy. Try to go there every week))

Best vegan food joint for vegan "junk food".  The also have helther options like bowls but I got a burger.  The loaded nachos were especially good with the "meat" and probably my favorite part of the meal (which is saying a lot considering I'm not a fan of nachos).  Also the oatmeal cookie cream sandwich is THE BEST. A must try if your ever in the area whether your vegan or not.
Tasty, quality vegan food. Diverse menu, reasonable prices, nice atmosphere. I will return. I had the jalapeno burger and the thai soup. Enjoyed them both, but that soup was absolutely divine!

Good vegan burgers! Stopped in to have lunch and was very satisfied! My partner and I shared a avocado beetroot burger, the creamy mushroom burger with creamy garlic fries. We couldn't decide which burger we liked more- but the garlic fries left us with some serious garlic breath and were Very garlicky (we could feel the burn).  Vampire-free for 4 hours and counting.

My 2nd time at this location and a much improved experience from my first time at this location.

Thank you for bringing back my favorite menu item, that definitely made my food experience a positive one. Thank you for the speedy service and cozy environment you all have created amidst the hustle and bustle of the city of Los Angeles.

Always a pleasure to dine with Native Foods Cafe, helps all vegetarians feel better knowing that we have place to eat when on the go.
The food is Amazing!! Came here with the family and everyone was very satified with food and service. Would definitely come again and recommend to others!

Although the food is good but not out of the world, i appreciate how many options their menu has spanning at least 3 Southeast Los Angeles. Definitely my go to when i crave Los Angeles food but cant decide between everything. 
Service is pretty good here as well. They can get pretty busy but they always make an effort to make sure everything is good and very responsive to requests.
Indonesian food and the scene at this spot is great. got there near seven, it wasn't very crowded. service treated us so nice. it has a great interior.

Modestly-priced good food served by a friendly (family-owned, I think) staff.  Larger people (like me) may want to pay a little extra to double the meat portion if you're extra hungry.  Mostly tables for couples, but one section can handle a party of 10-12.
Indonesian food, yeah, awesome. Entered near nine, it wasn't busy. The service here is friendly. Prices are fair I would say. I can see why they have so many good reviews.
Fine location for Indonesian food. Staff is always super even when they have a full house. The bill was good for how much you get. Feels like a place in Los Angeles I loved.
Shamshiri it's a well known Persian restaurant with delicious Persian style dishes, amazing kabobs and rice with saffron. The staff are friendly and helpful.
Great food I recommend Zereshk Polo with chicken kabobs. Great food huge portions nice staff. Get there
So cozy place, lovely service and great food
Great tasting food. Generous portions. Authentic Persian atmosphere & decor. Reasonable prices. Great team.
Good food and fast service, not crowded, no waiting time to get seated. Best place to go on Christmas and Easter, the Persians don't celebrate these holidays so they are open.
Great Japanese food.  Delicious choice of rolls and noodles.  Great value.  Good service.  Would highly recommend.
Food is consistent and very good, however service was incredibly slow tonight, which is tough when you have a large group with 5 children between them.

My three year old loves this place and so do I! We first started coming for happy hour and would walk out of there for less than $20. It was amazing. We love the service and the kid-friendly atmosphere, hello kitty plates are always a crowd pleaser. We usually get the $15 special and split it, tons of food and good soba noodles. Now we are moving away and will miss them! Thanks to Taiko for two years of yummy food.
The rate is 4 stars.  It can get pricey and the service can be a little bad when busy but I think it is worth it.
Very kind and friendly staff. Good quality of authentic and traditional Japanese food. Also this is the place to eat some Soba noodle in the area. Very reasonable price for daily use.
Really enjoyed this place.  Food was soooo good, portions were huge, and the service was Excellent!  We really enjoyed the cozy atmosphere and the way the staff made you feel like you were family.
Great service and good food! We are lucky to have the little gem within walking distance. I'm sure we'll be back. Next time I plan on sitting on their patio!
Wonderful little Italian restaurant with dog friendly seating. Food was delicious and service was excellent.
Delicious delicious delicious! The manager there was one of the nicest restaurant managers I've ever met. And the fact that he was a Sicilian fratello, I will be back there soon again and again!
nice and friendly staff, food is delicious I will go back again

I keep coming here for years to enjoy live jazz music. Here are awesome vibe and great decorations. Last time we've been there we saw a Jazz show. It was just perfect but our waiter was too pushy asking us to order some food and drinks every 10 minutes. Overall, it was a nice experience.

My first time at this exquisite club. Its visual atmosphere was fantastic. The bar area is modest size but very elegant and comfortable. There is a stage for live music and an outstanding group was performing. Large art panels add to the nature of the location's atmosphere. The place was packed with happy lively people. Valet parking was available. The folks who ran the location were very friendly and warm. I wished I could have stayed longer. I will return soon.

Wonderful place, excellent food and service for a fabulous evening out.  A must go, first rate supper club.  My wife Anastasia and I saw the incredible Nan Schwartz perform some of her most beautiful music with her 17 piece orchestra.  Herb Alpert was in the audience to see Nan along with several other celebrities.  What a place... what a night!!!  Cheers!

The best jazz club in Greater Los Angeles area, by far. Class, style, art, and exquisite interior design frame selected talented musicians every night.
Thank you Mr Alpert for continuing to make our lives better with quality entertainment.

Love this place!  Classy place for live music and dinner.  It's a supper club.  Check calendar to see who's playing.  You will absolutely need to make reservations or you will be standing.  Also, for those that are cost conscious this is not for you...2-3 drink minimum plus $20.00 door fee and if you add dinner my bill for two with 2 drinks for both was over $250.00.  One last remark...its an excellent place for couples.
I never imagined shaved ice could be this good. Must try
First time I tried shaved ice and enjoyed it.
Just like Hawaii!!! Great shaved ice.
Da best shaved ice in Los Angeles.   Great syrup flavors, passion fruits and POG.  The price is good for LA, $4.25 for child, regular $5.75

Hands down the best dessert you will ever have the luxury of enjoying. The owner even went out of her way to introduce me to the new experience and suggested several crowd favorites to help me along the way. I travel two hours specifically for this dessert.

I finally visited Pan Pacific Park Lake with my bf and pups last weekend and it was a lovely experience. I was so happy we found parking right away. The lake is small so it's easy to walk around the whole thing. I loved that there were so many people take photos of the flowers blooming on the water. Definitely a relaxing spot to take a walk! Only taking off a star because I could do without all the tents.

Nice park.  Plenty of space.  Several picnic tables, some with BBQs.  Generally well maintained, paved walkways can have mud runoff during rain.  Has a nice loop with gentle grades, good for a run or power walk. I walked my dog here for years.  They don't allow dogs off leash, and you can get a ticket for doing so....but I regularly let her off leash to play with other dogs, just keep an eye out for Park Rangers.
Great park to take your kids to. When it gets busy parking will be hard to get. Play ground is very nice. Has a soccer field and basketball court as well.
A rope swing overlooking the city.. what more can you want!? This is so much fun and a must for visitors and locals alike.
Decent hiking area. Enjoy overlooking the city after climbing over the numerous pebbles and gigantic rocks. We had the opportunity to see old areas of the previous zoo location.

While on a business trip to LA in 1995, amongst other areas of interest the entourage stopped here for a quick look-see, and it was not what I expected. It’s kind of tucked in downtown and while interesting it’s not a big place. They may have renovated it during these last 25 years, but I don’t know if this is the case. Still, prehistory is one of my interests and it is a bucket-list check off as far as I’m concerned.

I'd heard about this place all my life and finally got the chance to visit. Incredible! It's a beautiful park in its own right, but then you also have these fascinating tar pits. The largest is the size of a small lake (it's called the Lake Pit), and the smallest are only a few feet across, yet they all managed to trap many prehistoric animals. There's a museum next to the park that has exhibits about the pits and the fossils that have been pulled out. The park is free to visit, but there's an admission fee to enter the museum.

Loved this place after hearing about it all my life. There is tar randomly bubbling up out of the ground, so watch where you step. Lots of interactive displays and exhibits that kids can play with inside the museum. Getting to take a look at active dig sites is pretty exciting, too. The grounds are clean and well kept, and there is plenty space outdoors for little ones to run around. Great way to spend an afternoon. If you've got a kid that loves dinosaurs, this is a must.

I’ve heard about this spot forever and finally got a chance to see it in person. The museum has fantastic displays and does a great job explaining how the tar pits were formed, why/how the animals died and the procedures for excavating the sites. There are hands-on displays as well as movies to watch. After you leave the museum you get to follow a path around the area. This path takes you through active excavation sites as well as fenced off areas Protecting visitors from at that’s bubbling up from the ground. You can actually see the gas bubbling up from the tar. Parking is very reasonable with a huge lot next door to the museum. The fee was $15 for the day. A short walk from this location and you’ll be at the Urban Lights and the Petersen Auto Museum. All in all a wonderful place to visit!

Took the grandkids ages 3, 5 & 7. They enjoyed it. There's enough interactive learning displays to entertain them and not too large of a museum for them to lose interest. The 7 year old was especially excited and he had a genuine interest in dinosaurs and the like. Even though the Tar Pits are of the last ice age and not the prehistoric time period, it still covers history up to 35 million years ago (the large dinosaurs like the tyrannosaurus went extinct 65 million years ago and before the tar pits were formed). They have an active excavation pit ongoing that is viewable.

This is my favourite photo gallery in LA - If you are looking for the best in fine art photography this is the place. Been there many many times - Mark Seliger opening yesterday. If you have not been and care for photography - you really missed something.

This place is among the top 3 must-go-to of all places I recommend to friends or business partners visting.
Excellent dialogue between KCRWs Jason Bentley and star photog Mark Seliger
Excellent gallery specializing in photography. Probably best like it in Los Angeles.
Great Herb Ritts show last night will go back.
An amazing gallery with stellar shows
So comfortable.. and welcoming..cant do enough for you ..and very friendly
Welcoming host, generous provisions and close to all facilities but a little tired looking. Good value for money
Great place to stay . Fully equipped cottages. Old world charm . Reasonable prices . Lovely town Georgetown tasmania . Thank u Clo u r a great hostess . 😁👍
Beautiful old home and food in tearoom is good
Awesome friendly eclectic place to stay

Absolutely loved this experience. I've wanted to eat here since seeing it featured on several shows in and around the LA area. It did not disappoint.  The line was long (for good reason) but the ladies working the kitchen and counter handled it like champs. They kept everything right on target and with a menu as extensive as theirs, that's a feat in and of its self. If you come to LA you have to eat at Pinks!

Pink's Hot Dogs is one of the most famous iconic landmarks in Los Angeles, having been at this location on La Brea Avenue since 1946. They have a large menu of burgers and sides, but they are best known, of course, for their hot dogs. Their huge menu is varied and their "specials" are named after famous people, places, or things; the combinations and toppings are nearly endless.

After deliberating for 15 minutes while waiting in line, I finally decided on a spicy Polish Pastrami-Swiss hot dog for $8. The polish dog was different than their usual, as it was very spicy, flavorful, and smoky, bursting with juiciness. Their salty, rich pastrami was also grilled and delicious, leaving me with a greasy, but extremely satisfying result. Exactly what I wanted.

The place gets busy here with long lines and orders, however the lines tend to move fast. By the time it's your turn your order should be said perfectly. Pinks has been around for so long now it's no wonder they are still respected for their food and style. I recommend this spot to everyone I know. The choices are near endless, so there's something here for you too. Enjoy!

Picks is the best place for anything Hot Dogs... We have been going there for over 25 years... It's the same every time... Yummy and delicious.... If you haven't had Pinks Hot Dog....you haven't had a real Hot Dog.... Be prepared to wait in a line...a long line... Triple that if it's the weekend.... But it's worth it... Totally worth it...

Most certainly a 5 star as far as hot dog venues go! I like to visit hot-dog spots for fun when traveling and this place should be on any hot-dog lovers list of must try spots Great for lunch, dinner or late night fun. Menu has a LARGE selections of dogs. Can be crowded if you go at peak times but lines usually move fairly fast. Who knows you may run into a celebrity as well.

Fantastic vegan food!  I ate here a few times while spending a week in a nearby hotel.  All their food is delicious!  I recommend the Impossible bacon cheeseburger and their spare ribs were great, too.
Amazing AMAZING food!! I sadly moved out of state but luckily come back and get to visit this amazing place every month. Seriously I dream about their food. BEST vegan food hands down!!!

I said why not let me try something new you live one life you can't always be picky, well it's your life you do what the f... You want to do. I said let me try something new and let me tell you the sweet & sour chicken vegan plate was really good. The food had so much flavor, will be coming here back soon.

Best vegan place I've been to in L.A.! Love the Thai ice tea. Beef jerky, impossible burger, garlic pepper, so good. I go so often that they know our basic order. Even my non vegan friends and family eat here. Love it!

Great taste, nice staff. They have a great selection of Thai dishes and American staples. I love the papaya salad, and their noodle dishes, but you can also get an Impossible burger here. Something for everyone.

During our visit, the food was good but the service - not so much.

We arrived at around 10am and were quoted a 20minute wait time with 10 parties ahead of us. We ended up waiting an hour. Our names were called after 30minutes only for us to learn that our table was given to another party. We were ultimately seated in a side room with patio furniture.

Also note that Blu Jam allows people to use Yelp to add themselves to the wait list, so the amount of people inside is not representative.

Once seated, we waited quite some time to get our drinks - we were told that "there weren't enough clean cups". Our waitress seemed stretched very thin.

Our food was delivered by a more relaxed and charismatic gentleman, which helped us enjoy our food.

The Sicilian Scramble was good, but the crunchy French toast was a little disappointing. Maybe there was too much hype. Coffee is also limited to one refill.

Of all the brunch choices in Santa Monica, I don't think this one is worth the hassle.

Their potatoes are SO GOOD! The spinach, sun-dried tomatoes, and mushrooms were savory and delicious. Even the english muffin was perfectly toasted. My girlfriend ordered their latte with almond milk, which we both really enjoyed. They were super busy when we came in, but the wait was surprisingly short.

The Burgundy omelette was so savory and incredibly good. The potatoes has so much flavor and that home made jam was so delicious. The wait wasn't too bad, and the service was ok, but they were very busy! Our food came out quickly and we enjoyed everything.

So I literally found out about this place because of someone I follow on You tube. (Shout out to Aysha  Harun) she gave this place great reviews.  So I check it out on Yelp... All I can say is I was not disappointed.

I started off with a ginger shot. Ooh, hot and tart. It is sprinkled with I believe cayman pepper. Very cleaning is what I can say. Both hubby and I had it. 

For brunch I had the Blu Jam Benedict and my husband had a breakfast burrito.  Plenty of food and very tasty.

I got there cereal dipped French toast to go. It was still delicious once I got it home warmed it up and ate it with coffee. 

Give this place a try, you won't be disappointed.

This place was great! We had heard so much about this French toast made with brioche and Kellogg’s for a crispy and delicious treat. 🤤 It did not disappoint! Service e was really good and although our food took a bit long, it was worth it! Highly recommend this place. We had both regular and french press coffee and they were both really good as well. We were also very happy to see that this place is pet friendly because we saw a couple dogs walk in with their families. This place offers outdoor seating for guests and their pets. 👍🏼 overall, very pleasant experience.

I love going to Canter's Deli.  I've been going here for years.  It's right in the heart of the Fairfax district of Los Angeles.
      Weather it's for one of their amazing sandwiches (I prefer the pastrami sandwich myself) or their soups or knishes or one of the myriad of menu items,  you just can't go wrong.  And that's before you even get to the on sight bakery items (which are amazing in, and of themselves.  
      The best part........They're open 24 hours a day,  7 days a week.  If you've never been, you need to go to this Los Angeles classic

Everyone knows Canters, and it's not for nothing! Go eat there. Everything is great. The bar has great music as well. And don't forget, they're open 24 hours, which makes them my absolute favorite place in LA for a nice meal!

Be prepared to be stuffed into a booth that’s way too small.  My boyfriend is just a medium guy and could barely fit.  Our legs were on top of each other.  If you’re not eating breakfast, be prepared to pay over $15 for a sandwich. $15 will get you a half a sandwich and a cup of soup, actually.  Definitely not a budget friendly place.

That being said,  their kosher selection is good and the quality of their food is excellent. They also give you generous portions.  So you definitely get what you pay for.  If it were for my physical discomfort, I would have probably given it 5 stars.

One of the best places left to get lox and bagels. They are also open 24 hours & there have been times when I wake up at 3:00 in the morning craving lox & bagel breakfast and i go there at 4:00 a.m. and have my breakfast and get home before the traffic gets to bad.  The atmosphere is late sixties early seventies and they play music of that era as well. last night when I went there they were playing Deep Purple - Highway star as well as Led Zepplin and Yes - Roundabout Van Morrison and Blue Oyster Cult. Definitely my kind of music.

Had another great meal here.  I had the pannini with brisket and muenster cheese.  I think they call it the Little Stack.  Very tender, flavorful.  Service was great.  Wait wasn't too bad for Sunday lunch on a beautiful but cold day.

The food is average, but the margaritas are the best  The service is pretty solid. Parking is not great. Unless you can find street parking, valet is required after a certain hour. It's easy to spot from the road, and it's an old school LA haunt.

I was a little shocked - I never knew food could taste like this.
The soup tasted like a touch of heaven and the scallops were the best I have ever tasted.
All in all - a truly great meal!

Stylish interior and servers wearing traditional dresses. It's definitely the most Mexican-looking Mexican restaurant I've ever been to. :) During our visit there was a live mariachi band, if that's your thing. The food is good and reasonably priced considering the location and the uniqueness of the place. The house margarita is very good! Only giving 4 starts because the place was very noisy and rather hectic for my taste, but to someone else this might actually add to the appeal.

If you're looking for an authentic Mexican experience then look no further than El Coyote. You'll find the waitresses dressed in traditional Mexican garb treating you with that warm hospitality that Mexico is famous for. If you're going to get one thing on the menu make sure it's the crispy hard shell tacos. They're quite flavorful and filling.

Haven't been there for close to 10 years. Margaritas were around $5 back then. The people who work there are still great. Usually smiling and happy. Some have been there longer than 10-15 years. The food is still the same. The flavor hasn't changed at all. Good TexMex cuisine. It was nice to be there last night with good friends.

Add my name to the list of Guelaguetza fanatics. I went with my family once after hearing non-stop raves about this place. Then, I talked it up so much that my bosses got me a gift card as a thank you gift. Both times were wonderful experiences. And let's just be real: it's all about the mole. They know how to make it, and we love it. Both times we have ordered the Festival of Moles and another big platter of meat and vegetables, and they've been great together. Maybe next time we'll order something else to go with our mole, but maybe not. The service is great: friendly, welcoming, and not at all pretentious. The decor is just right. And the Live music is great. Just be warned: this place is busy on Saturday nights. I recommend getting here early to beat the rush.

Holy Meat Heaven!!! Went here with some work buddies (group of chefs) and we were blown away! Everything we ate delicious and we got a lot of food. My only criticism is there was at least another 4 person meal's worth of food that we couldn't order because we stood no chance of finishing it. I'm kidding of course, that's not a criticism, it just means we will have a tough time deciding: Do we A. Order the same thing because it was so good or B. Try something new 

Amazing. Keep up the delicious work!

Great Mexican food in a vibrant setting. Our party of six ordered family style and no one was disappointed. As noted on previous posts the mole was amazing. We sampled the flight, yum. Make reservations and parking is not fun, but the food is well worth the trek.

Food is definitely not your every day type so coming here was a treat and definitely a great experience. At first for some reason the food reminded me a bit of Guatemalan dishes, and it should since it's from Oaxaca (South of Mexico), but they do have their own distinctive awesome taste. Prices are good; very busy and seating is a bit crowded however, it didn't affect the timing or quality of the food or their service. Parking is like $10 or something so be ready- live music was excellent- overall service and cleanings of the place was on point. Food portions are a good size so have an appetite when you come here. You will not be disappointed.

As someone of the fair-skinned persuasion, I still have a lot to learn about mole, but this place blew anything I've had before out of the water. I can never make up my mind when ordering because they're all so damned good! One of my favorite and probably most unique spots in the city.

Love their vegan options, their service, and their atmosphere! They use Field Roast vegan cheese which is definitely one of the nicer brands out there, so I really appreciate that. Bloody Maria was delicious, but their margarita just tasted like OJ and tequila so that was a bummer. Besides that, everything I've tried has been good.
Fresh baked goodies and a hipster take on diner classics. (Egg sandwich with avocado, of course). The service is fast and the coffee is bitter.

Outstanding spot for tasty american food. Great place to chill, get away, eat some good food. I'll return with my coworkers. The bill was fair for the quality of the food. I can see why they have so many great reviews.
american food here - great. I've had nothing but pleasant experiences here and plan to keep coming back. The bill was reasonable I would say.

The worst breakfast ever!  I had such high hopes for this place when I saw scrambled tofu on the menu.  The pancakes weren’t even edible - burnt and tasted like cardboard - like somebody made the batch and left out salt, sugar and oil.  Nothing tasted good.  I went there this morning after leaving a local club @ 2am.  I had the American Breakfast - scrambled tofu, chicken sausage, and pancakes.  Nothing was properly seasoned.  My hot chocolate was way too sweet. How do you serve pancakes without bringing butter?  The waitress took the meal off the bill, thankfully, but she wasn’t gracious.
Was walking by and stumbled onto this place.  Great sliders and reasonably priced.  One of the few places that serves food late. Nice decor. I enjoyed the experience and food
Excellent place for delicious American food. I will be back with my coworkers. This place has an awesome atmosphere. Kinda of like a place in Houston that I enjoyed.
Excellent service.  The various meals were all quite flavorful and we left clean plates. Exceptional all together.
American food and the atmosphere here is above par. Great place to relax, people watch, eat good food or all the above.  I'll return with my relatives.
Pot roast and butterscotch pudding. Perfection. Every time.
Tasty food and not spicy. If you want them spicy, you tell the waiter. Staff is very friendly and sincere. Lamb, vegetables and rice was fine. We paid 60 euros at dinner for 2 people.

Loved it here. Its a bit tucked away from the main Street and probably wouldn't have found it myself if it wasn't for a recommendation, but I'm really happy that we did find it. We went in for a quick bite but I would be very happy to spend the evening here nibbling on different courses. The owner is very proud and the food really good.  Nicely spiced and the sides are fresh. Definitely visit.
Great food! Friendly guy running the place, with everything looking tidy and having a proper Indian atmosphere. It feels warm and welcome.
Really great place to eat! Very friendly staff/owner, food is delicious. Be carefully with hot or very hot, the hot was already really hot for me 😅.
The best Indian food after long time in europe. Try the Butter Chicken and lamb shahi korma with peswaria naan amazing tasty.
Regular

No me explico como este tipo de establecimiento le dan una licencia de turismo para que operen con tanta impunidad y colocan en la recepción un documento que avala que fue supervisado por el ente rector, por Dios vayan e inspeccionen y verán que no cumple con los requerimientos mínimos para operar como hotel y menos en esa jurisdicción de Chacao.
Problemas de agua y con algunos elementos esenciales como el aire acondicionado. La ubicación ideal, cerca de muchas cosas incluyendo una estación del metro.
Muy cómodo, bueno y limpio. Son muy atentos con el cliente. Las habitaciones son limpias. El agua llegua las 8 am y 10 pm. Me gustó el lugar además de ser muy céntrico.
Buena opción relación precio valor
